Around the World

JAMMU, India —— An explosion
aboard a train headed toward J ammu-
Kashmir yesterday killed 12 people
and injured 39. The explosion in the
train’s sleeper car occurred as the
train was leaving the station in
Ambala, 250 miles south of Jammu—
Kashmir.

The train had been at the station
for a 15-minute stopover right before
the explosion occurred. Police said
that no group has claimed responsibil-
ity yet, but Kashmiri separatists have
previously tried to blow up trains by
planting bombs on the tracks.
Associated Press

BELGRADE, Yugoslavia — Tens of
thousands of people protested against
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic
yesterday because of a court ruling
two weeks ago that annulled opposi-
tion victories in ‘local elections.
During a snowstorm, 10,000 stu-

dents marched through blustery
Belgrade, some carrying ﬂowers and
others carrying signs that said “We are
not fascists.” Government buildings
were bombarded by snowballs later in
the day-when 60,000 people gathered
to protest. Associated Press

Across the Nation

WATERFORD, Conn. ——- A
Greyhound bus carrying holiday trav-
elers hit ice and ﬂipped over early
Monday morning just outside of
Waterford. Traffic was backed up for
hours as the 16 injured people were
removed from the bus. The victims
ranged in age from 6 months to 29
years.

A spokesman for the Lawrence &
Memorial Hospital said that the
injuries appeared to be minor. One of
the passengers, Jose Veliz, said that
approximately 35 passengers were
sleeping when the bus wrecked.
