UPMC launches revolutionary
cardiac arrest program downtown

 

Jennifer Halu k

A new research program that may save
more lives from sudden cardiac arrest is now
stationed downtown and is one of the ﬁrst in
its kind in the country.

The Galbreath Company, the
University of Pittsburgh Medical Center,
and Survivalink Corporation of Minneapolis
have begun a joint research program to pro
vide early treatment for cardiac arrest vic-
tims at the USX Tower in Pittsburgh.

Sudden cardiac arrest is a leading cause
of death in the United States. The great
majority of cardiac arrests occur out of the
hospital and are due to a ventricular ﬁbrilla-
tion — a state in which the heart quivers in
an uncoordinated manner and is unable to
effectively pump blood.

The only effective treatment of this
abnormal heart activity is to electrically
countershock the heart through a process of
deﬁbrillation. The earlier the countershock is
perfonned, the greater the likelihood of sur-
vival and the less brain damage will occur.

This research program was created in
response to a call by the American Heart
Association for a wider availability of deﬁb-
rillation devices. The AHA also hopes to
provide ﬁrst responders with access and the
proper training to the device.

According to the AHA, ﬁrst responders
are emergency or community services per-
sonnel who are expected to respond to med-
ical emergencies, and who are typically the

ﬁrst on the scene. They can include para-
medics, EMTs, Basic Life Support
Ambulance personnel, ﬁreﬁghters, volun—
teers, and police officers.

Through this program, Survivalink
hopes to see the deﬁnition of ﬁrst responders
to include hospital staif, personnel in physi-
cians’ oﬁices, commercial security person-
nel, and staff people at health clubs and golf
courses.

‘This part of the study at the USX
Tower is to help determine the impact that
public access to autorrrated deﬁbrillations
will have on cardiac arrest survival rates in
commercial office buildings,” said VIDCC
Mosesso, M.D., assistant professor of emer-
gency medicine at UPMC.

The program will include the use of an
automated extemal deﬁbrillator, known as
Vrvalink, developed and marketed by the
Galbreath Company. The device which is
inexpensive and lightweight, was approved
by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
in February 1995. To date, more than 20
lives have been saved by the use of this
device.

“Survivalink is pleased to see. this his-
toric study launched and that we are part of
this important program,” said Bryon
Gilman, Survivalink chairman. “Studies like
this are the pioneering efforts that will lead to
a national solution to sudden cardiac arrest.
When we ﬁrst started working on a deﬁbril-
lator, we envisioned the day when oﬁice
buildings, sports complexes and police cars
would all be equipped with one.”

