Beer, wine, liquor: it’s lalljusl
an advertisement for alcohol

Liquor: the hard stuff, vodka, cognac, whiskey, rum,
the green stuff, the blue stuff. Heck, it’s Christmas, don’t
forget the eggnog. Whatever you call it, Representative
Joe Kennedy (D-Massachusetts) says liquor should not be
advertised on T.V. 

Isn’t that a strange statement coming from a man
whose grandfather made big bucks peddling whiskey and
whose uncle is the most public drinker on the Hill? They
made their choices, why can’t we make ours?

However, beer and wine are already advertised, and
so it seems a rather dubious distinction to make. After all,
each contains alcohol — the substance Congress is trying
to regulate. Though the concentration. differs between
liquor, beer, and wine, the effects are the same. As we all
learned in ninth grade health class (or perhaps AA if you
missed that lesson), one 12—ounce can of beer equals one
glass of wine, which in turn equals one shot of hard
liquor. P

Yes, we know all about alcohol abuse, irresponsible
consumption, drunken drivers, and the whole nine yards.

However, we believe in the ability of the vast majority of »

adults who choose to drink to do so in a moderate and
responsible fashion. One way to increase. awareness of
alcohol and its effects is through experience and perhaps
even advertising.

We don’t appreciate the possibility of Washington
deciding that we are too stupid to make these informed
choices for ourselves, that we can somehow handle the
spectacle of Budweiser’s friendly frogs without becom-
ing morally depraved alcoholics; but we can’t take the
idea of watching a St. Bernard frolic through the snow
with a ﬂask of brandy around its neck.

What is possible and desirable is that all adults be
educated and informed in order to make sensible choices.
Perhaps the government should be a little more concerned
with education, and a little less concerned with prohibi-
tion.

