There are two modes of thinking
and two ways of looking at everything.
One is the scientific mode which
involves underlying structure and func-
tion. The opposite and complementary
mode of thinking is often called the
romantic mode. It involves emotion,
impression, and intuition. Many see one
mode as more valid than the other.
However, I think that much can be
gained from realizing that they are
equally valid.

There is underlying structure to just
about everything. Even music, which is
touted as anartistic outlet, can be broken
down into scientiﬁc relationships and
structure. Certain notes sound good
together, and certain notes do not.
Computers can create some pretty amaz-
ing compositions when all or some of
the rules of music theory are pro-
grammed into them. Music is a language
with rules and functions much like math-
ematics, but to think entirely in this man—
ner is a mistake. It minimizes the emo-
tion involved and expressed in music.
When music is reduced to a set of rules
and random notes within those rules, it
becomes more of a game than an art.
There is, however, something to be
gained by the scientiﬁc interpretation of

