music. Artists who gauge playing mere-
ly on emotion, with little or no music
theory, can not create as complex and
interesting-sounding music as those who
incorporate theory into their work. But
one must remember that on the other
hand, music without emotion (i.e. music
totally based on structure) loses one of
the most valuable properties we value in
a good piece of music. By exploiting
both modes of thought for what they are
useful for, one can   
transcend the ordi-
nary and create some-
thing truly amazing,
on both the structural
and emotional levels.
Modern western
medicine is another
good example of
where these two
modes of thinking clash. Modern medi—
cine is based on the tenets of biology and
the underlying structure and function of
the human body. Eastern medicine (par-
ticularly in China) is based on the man-
aging of a universal spiritual energy
called Chi. Acupuncture and acupressure
are both proven viable methods of treat-
ment for many things. Western science
can try to explain away the effects of
these practices by saying that the pres-
sure points correspond with nerve end-
ings, etc. But we must remember that

   

Eastern science can do the same thing by
reversing the argument. As a human
race, we always try to explain away
other philosophies by giving them the
name of coincidence in our own person-
al reality. There is no real way to detect
the absolute truth of something. One can
only judge a philosophy or method by
