Logic and intuition: neither is complete without the other

ical miracle.

This merging of the two thought
processes is applicable to anything. In
Robert Pirsig’s book, “Zen and the Art
of Motorcycle Maintenance,” Pirsig
talks of this joining as something he
calls quality. Since absolute truth is a
rather squirrely entity, quality or useful-
ness is the best way to judge modes of
thought. He states that we are extremely
prejudiced about running down other

_ people’s ghosts when we are equally

superstitious and ignorant about our
own. By other people’s ghosts, he means
religion and romantic modes of thought,
and by ours he means science and the
scientific method. The point of the book
and this article is that we should elirni—

nate this prejudice and see both on an

equal level when pertaining to quality.
Most things can be explained in
terms of structure and scientiﬁc analysis,“
just as most things can be explained in
terms of mysticism and intuition.
Neither is complete, but one seems to
pick up where the other leaves off. The
key is to see these for what they are:
approximations of true reality, which we
as humans may" never see. Our only tool
for refining our personal reality is judg-
ment based on quality and usefulness.
Jay DeMartino thinks that philosophy is
one of the best and most eﬂective pro-
crastination tools ever invented.

Something tells me it's time to get the heck out of Dodge

  

Although the presidential
election is over, I am still skeptical
as to what the future holds. Were
people pressing buttons and
pulling levers for the country or
for their health? AmeriKKKa
chose its big cheese, and I still feel
like we walked into a, trap. The
entire political process has the
nose—wrinkling stench of a bad
action—adventure movie. I
remember how it all began.

My journey begins in early
‘96. I am assigned to bring home
a competent president to America.
I am warned to beware of power-
ful forces threatening to control
the country for their own greedy
gains: General Gingrich Zod, and
his American Contracts, Money
Man Forbes, and Perot the
Ghostface Mercenary.

Through my expedition, I am
tracked and attacked by savage
Democrat and Republican tribes,
yielding blowguns and issue-
tipped darts. I am held captive for
months, being fed poisonous pro-
paganda. They worship holy ani-
mal symbols like the donkey and
elephant. The haunting rhythms

of tiibal drums and saxophones
rise over the village, thumping
and tooting the war cries of “Dole

Man” and “America the
Beaut' .”
I am brought before the high ,

priests, Clinton and Dole. I recog-
nize them from early secret files.
They are actually traveling rr1agi—
cians whose plane crashed long
ago in the deepest part of the
"media jungle.

Now, they are masquerading
as prophets. They dazzle the
natives with magical metaphors
and promises. “Behold as we bal-
ance the budget and cut taxes.”
The natives watch as Clinton and
Dole make social programs disap-
pear, striking fear into their strug-
gling hearts.

But -they each crave total
power. Gathering their political
forces, they wage war against
each other. Innocent bodies are
caught in the crossfire, including
myself.

Just when it seems like the
mission will be a failure, a Tarzan-
like yell is heard from Texas. Like
the hero who comes just in the
nick of time, Perot the mercenary
has come to save me. He swings

from the money tree into battle,
tossing $100 grenades. But, being
a mercenary, he is ultimately out

for hirrrself. He too wants the

power. But he has no game plan.

- Under the clouds- of confu-
sion, Imake my escape. I gain
some distance and set up traps to
slow them down. But they are
swift and agile, dodging welfare
refonn and affrrrnative action vine
slings. Clinton and. Dole hurdle
tax reform issues like Olympic
track stars, and despite their
obscure differences, combine to
keep Perot a distant third.

I reach a clearing and cast my
eyes skyward. Over the horizon
of TV and newspaper trees, I can
see a sign in bright red neon
lights. It says, “Vote Here.” My
mission is almost complete. But I
am tired of being chased. I can’t
keep running away. I must face
them here.

I turn to see them walk slow-
ly into the clearing. Showdown.
Wah—aah—Wah—ah-aaahhh, Wah-
wah-waaahhh. I jump back into a
karate kid crane stance as they
approach. They hesitate.

“Alright, you want me? Try
to take me, punks,” I say.

They charge me. But with
lightening speed I strike back.
‘What do you plan to do about
public schools? Student loans?
Health care? What community
programs will be out? What are
my chances of having a job when
I graduate?”

I knock Perot out with the
first blow. Dole blocks and ducks
the issues, but he too soon falters.
I ask, “How do you plan to handle
gun control?” '

“Well, Clinton hasn’t done
his job.”

I didn’t ask him about
Clinton, so I shot him.

Clinton is more tricky, more
cunning. The force is strong in
him. He blinds me with his sly fox
smile and uses soothing words to
clog my hearing. “I am like you. I
am one of you. I am your friend.
Here, have a McNugget.” He’s
sharp. He’s strong like the head
honcho at the end of a video
game.

But soon I peep his tech-
nique. He looks good, sounds
good, and gives a good speech.
He’s telling me what he thinks I
want to hear. He’s going for my
senses and my emotions.

I step back and pull out a
scarf and ear plugs. I insert the ear
plugs, put the scarf around my
eyes and tie it tightly. He can’t get
to me now. I use my nose to sniff
him out. There’s a strong B.S.
smell to what he’s saying. I con-
nect with a good stiff left jab to his
eye. I take off the blindfold in
time to see him hitting the ground.
I turn and dash for the sign.

I have reached. my destina-
tion, the voting booth. I open the
curtains and am confronted by
names. A ghostly voice suddenly
speaks. “You must choose wisely,
my son.” As if I was picking out
the true Holy Grail among the
phonies, I scan the names.

But something doesn’t feel
right. I spot the names Clinton and
Dole. This feels like a set up. Just
before I pull a lever, the ghostly
voice turns to evil guy chuckles. I
jump back and look around hys-
terically. I hear a rumbling sound.
I stick my head through the cur-
tains just in time to see the large
boulder come thundering towards
me.

