Hockey

over Hartford.

Pens’ Head Coach Ed
Johnston made some happy faces
when he put Mario Lemieux, Ron
Francis, and Jaromir Jagr on the
same line entering last weekend.
Jagr, the NHL Player of the Month
for November, responded with a
his second hat trick of the season in
the harpooning of the Whalers on
Saturday.

Still, Hartford surprisingly
remains in a ﬁrst-place tie with the
Buffalo Sabres atop the division.
With only a plus-two goal differen-
tial and a 6-8-1 road record, how-
ever, critics don’t give this New
England team much more of a
chance. Sean Burke, Keith
Primeau, and the rest of the
Whalers are doing their very best
thus far to prove them wrong.

Philadelphia hopes its chances
of better play increase in the near
future with last week’s return of
Eric Lindros. The Flyers’ captain
has registered two assists thus far in
his ﬁrst four games back. Philly, at
14-12-1, are two games above .500
for the ﬁrst time this season.

The New York Rangers (10-
13-4) recently moved three games
closer to that feat. Mark Messier,
the NHL Player of the Week, led
the “Broadway Bombers” with ﬁve
goals in the undefeated Ranger
week (3-0), and look as if —they’re

 

ready to make their move to the top '

of the Atlantic. Gretzky, who
notched his 3,000th career point in
Sunday’s win over Montreal, will
need to step up his play as well.

At 16-8-1, the Dallas Stars are
already on top. The Stars have been
possibly one of the biggest surpris-
es of the season, leading the Central
since the start of the ‘96—’97 carn-
paign.

It’s not surprising to see that
the Colorado Avalanche (16-6-4)
continued from where they left off
in June. Joe Sakic and Peter
Forsberg lead the league with 11
goals and 25 assists each.

Goaltender Patrick Roy, ﬁrst in
the NHL with 15 wins, has been on
ﬁre lately. Roy has won eight of his
last 11 and boasted a 1.62 goals-
against-average for November.

' So there are still plenty of
questions to be answered with over
50 games to go this season:

Will Pittsburgh and the
Rangers rally? Can the Whalers
hold onto a playoff spot? Are the
Florida Panthers for real?

And of course - how many
more games will the Avalanche
win en route to another Stanley
Cup run? Or can they be stopped?

These and many other ques-
tions will be answered in the world
we call the National Hockey
League.

 

