Boo hoo, the Steelers
are hurting in The Pitt

from local and wire services

Football

- The Pittsburgh Steelers had expected
Greg Lloyd, Carnell Lake, Ray
Seals, Chad Brown, Yancey
Thigpen, and Mark Bruener to lead
them back to the Super Bowl. The
problem now is that all of these play-
ers are injured. Coach Bill Cowher is
hoping the replacements can at least
get his team a week off at playoff
time. Pittsburgh, Buffalo, and Kansas
City are fighting for second place in
the conference with identical 9-4
records.

° There’s a chance John Elway will
sit out Denver’s game at Green Bay
this Sunday. The Broncos’ quarter-
back is still nursing a pulled ham-
string, and Coach Mike Shanahan
says if the muscle is sore and tight he
won’t play Elway. Shanahan has the
luxury of resting his top players as the
12-1 Broncos have wrapped up home-
field advantage throughout the play-
offs.

Broncos offensive tackle Gary

Zimmerman will miss the Packers
game. after undergoing arthroscopic
surgery on his shoulder.
0 Another quarterback for the New
York Jets. What they really need, sev-
eral players say, is a change in atti-
tude.

Glenn Foley is in for Frank
Reich, who was in for Neil
O’Donnell. Foley will make his first
NFL start Sunday at New England.

- The Baltimore Ravens area bust on
the road — with opposing fans. When

the Ravens come to town, attendance

has dropped at each stadium.
Baltimore played before the smallest
crowds of the season in Pittsburgh,
Houston, Denver, Jacksonville, and
San Francisco.
College Football
- Lou Holtz might have coached his
last game at Notre Dame. The
Fighting Irish were officially taken
out of the running for an alliance
bowl, and the school’s athletics direc-
tor says they won’t accept bids from
the Copper or Independence Bowl.
What killed the Irish’s chance of get-
ting‘ in the Sugar, Fiesta, or Orange
Bowl was Saturday’s overtime loss to
Southern Cal. Notre Dame is 8-3 and
has dropped to 18th in the AP top 25.

A couple of other teams are mak-
ing plans for the postseason. West
Virginia has been invited to the Gator
Bowl to face North Carolina, and
Miami will take on Virginia in the
CarQues.t Bowl.

News Sports Briefing

- It appears Nebraska will have to play
the Big 12 Championship game with-
out its top tailback. Coach Tom
Osbourne says a foot injury will like-
ly keep Ahman Green out of
Saturday’s game against Texas.
Reserves Damon Benning. and
Deangelo Evans are also hurting.
Camps

- Kent State University will once
again be conducting the Rick
Rembielak Baseball Skills Clinics.
This winter they’ll belholding five
clinics which include a pitching and

catching clinic, a hitting clinic, an

overﬂow clinic for pitching and hit-
ting, a parent/child clinic, and a
infield defense clinic.

The clinics are open to campers
eight to 18 years of age, including

graduating seniors. The clinics will be -

instructed by the Kent baseball coach-
ing staff and team.

The first camp will be held from
Jan. 4-5. The second will take place
from Feb. 1-2. For further details call
the Kent baseball office at (330) 672-
3696.

Basketball
- You won’t want to miss out on the

amazing athleticism and non-stop

entertainment; it’s basketball with a
spin, Globetrotter style.

Tickets went on sale Friday, Nov.
29 for Pittsburgh’s only appearance of
the 1997 Harlem Globetrotters World
Tour. Known as the most recognized,
most popular, and most revered bas-
ketball team in the world, the Harlem
Globetrotters are suiting up for an all-
star performance at the Pittsburgh
Civic Arena Friday, Dec. 27 at 7:30

p.m.
Baseball

0 It appears Shawon Dunston’s heart
was left in Chicago —— not San

Francisco. After playing one season
for the Giants, the 33-year-old short-
stop is returning to the Cubs after
agreeing to a one-year contract worth
$2 million.

Dunston spent the first 11 years of
his big-league career with the Cubs
before signing with San Francisco last
January.

- Sid Fernandez has a new address.
After spending the last two seasons in
Baltimore and Philly, the left-hander
agreed yesterday with the Houston
Astros to a one—year deal heavy with
incentives. The 34-year-old Fernandez
was 3-6 last season with a 3.43 ERA.

The Astros also signed infielders
Pat Listach and Bill Spiers to one-
year contracts.

